'''Devil's Tower Road''' is a road in the [[British Overseas Territory]] of [[Gibraltar]]. The road in northeastern Gibraltar runs south of [[Gibraltar International Airport]], from [[Winston Churchill Avenue]] east to [[Eastern Beach Road]]. It was named after [[Devil's Tower (Gibraltar)|Devil's Tower]], a [[seventeenth century]] [[watchtower]] that was formerly at the eastern end of the road. [[Prehistoric]] man resided in what is now the Devil's Tower Road area, with [[Neanderthal]] remains found at [[Forbes' Quarry]] and the Devil's Tower [[rock shelter]]. The former discovery, made in 1848, represents the first discovery in history of a Neanderthal skull, known as [[Gibraltar 1]].

In 2007, the [[Government of Gibraltar]] revealed plans for a new [[airport terminal|terminal]] at [[Gibraltar International Airport]]. By 2011, Devil's Tower Road had been changed to a [[dual carriageway]], with on-street parking eliminated. A new access road was planned, such that Winston Churchill Avenue, which crosses the [[runway]], would no longer serve as the main road to the [[Gibraltar-Spain border]]. Rather, an access road would connect with the eastern end of Devil's Tower Road, pass through an underground tunnel, and after emerging north of the runway, extend to the west.  However, the contractor [[Obrasc<U+00F3>n Huarte Lain|OHL]] stopped working on the project and, by August 2011, had lost the <U+00A3>34M contract. In 2012, OHL initiated legal proceedings against the Government of Gibraltar, and the government started the tender process for the access road and tunnel project for the second time.

==Early History==

[[File:Dorothy Garrod.jpg|thumb|180px|left|[[Archaeologist]] [[Dorothy Garrod]] discovered [[Gibraltar 2]] in 1926.]]
[[File:Diagram of Devil's Tower.png|thumb|right|Diagram of [[Devil's Tower (Gibraltar)|Devil's Tower]] (first 3 images)]]
[[File:Neanderthal skull from Forbes' Quarry.jpg|thumb|right|[[Neanderthal]] skull, [[Gibraltar 1]], discovered by [[Edmund Henry R<U+00E9>n<U+00E9> Flint]] in 1848.]]
Devil's Tower Road is a [[Streets in Gibraltar|road in Gibraltar]], the British Overseas Territory at the southern end of the [[Iberian Peninsula]].<ref>{{cite web|title=List of Crown Dependencies & Overseas Territories|url=http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/publications-and-documents/treaties/uk-overseas-territories/list-crown-dependencies-overseas|work=fco.gov.uk|publisher=[[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]]|accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Neandertals' Last Stand Was in Gibraltar, Study Suggests|url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2006/09/060913-neanderthals.html|accessdate=9 October 2012|newspaper=National Geographic News|date=13 September 2006|author=Roach, John|agency=[[National Geographic Society]]}}</ref> The road in northeastern Gibraltar runs generally in an east-west direction, south of Gibraltar International Airport, North Front Cemetery, and Devil's Tower Camp. It provides access to the northern and eastern sides of Gibraltar, extending from the [[roundabout]] at Winston Churchill Avenue east to Eastern Beach Road.<ref name=discover/><ref>{{cite web|title=File:Gibraltar roads3.png|url=http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Gibraltar_roads3.png|work=commons.wikimedia.org|publisher=Wikimedia Commons|accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Map of Devil's Tower Road|url=http://maps.google.com/?q=36.147310,-5.344977&num=1&t=h&z=20|work=maps.google.com|publisher=[[Google Maps]]|accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref> It was named after Devil's Tower, a seventeenth century watchtower which was located at the eastern end of the road.<ref name=vox/><ref name=seven>{{cite news|title=A historical event|url=http://www.7daysgibraltar.com/article.php?id=4256|accessdate=8 October 2012|newspaper=7 Days - Gibraltar's Free Weekly Newspaper}}</ref> It was described by [[Sir George Cockburn, 10th Baronet]], as resembling an [[Irish round tower]]. The tower was constructed on a rock, whose size was just enough to serve as a foundation.<ref>{{cite book|title=A voyage to Cadiz and Gibraltar, up the Mediterranean to Sicily and Malta, in 1810 & II, including a description of Sicily and the Lipari Islands, and an excursion in Portugal, Volume 1|year=1815|publisher=J. Harding|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=7yMLAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA16&lpg=PA16&dq=demolition,+Devil's+Tower,+Gibraltar&source=bl&ots=aTxSo9gPDg&sig=2fQ7_dJyiCSsMWeDFGA7B7BPwU4&hl=en&sa=X&ei=5Jl0UIScKdTUyQHu4YHQDA&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAzgK#v=onepage&q=demolition%2C%20Devil's%20Tower%2C%20Gibraltar&f=false|author=Cockburn, Sir George|accessdate=9 October 2012|page=16}}</ref> It constituted part of the northern [[fortifications of Gibraltar]] mentioned in the 1713 [[Treaty of Utrecht]]. In 1727, the tower was captured in the [[Siege of Gibraltar (1727)|Siege of Gibraltar]]; it was later returned with the resumption of peace.<ref name=vox>{{cite news|title=PDP Against Re-naming of Our Historic Streets|url=http://vox.gi/local/3801-pdp-against-re-naming-of-our-historic-streets.html|accessdate=8 October 2012|newspaper=Vox - The Truly Independent Gibraltar Newspaper|date=28 May 2011}}</ref>

Prehistoric man resided in what is now the Devil's Tower Road area, at Forbes' Quarry, in the north face of the [[Rock of Gibraltar]]. This was the site of the 1848 discovery of the first Neanderthal skull by Lieutenant [[Edmund Henry R<U+00E9>n<U+00E9> Flint]] of the [[Royal Artillery]].<ref name=seven/><ref name=geology>{{cite journal|coauthors=Stringer, Christopher B.|title=Gibraltar woman and Neanderthal Man|journal=[[Geology Today]]|date=September-October 1997|url=http://www.scribd.com/doc/78902886/Gibraltar-Woman-and-Neanderthal-Man|accessdate=9 October 2012|author=Rose, Edward P. F.|page=179-184|publisher=Blackwell Science Ltd}}</ref><ref name=hominid/> The adult female skull is referred to as Gibraltar 1 or the Gibraltar Skull. Neanderthals were unknown at that time. Lieutenant Flint, secretary of the [[Gibraltar Scientific Society]], presented his discovery to the organization on 3 March 1848.<ref name=geology/><ref name=hominid/> Eight years later, in 1856, remains were discovered in a cave of the [[Neander Valley]] near [[D<U+00FC>sseldorf]], [[Germany]]. Those remains were described in 1864 as ''Homo neanderthalensis'' by W. King of [[Queen's College, Galway]], now University College.<ref name=geology/> Later that year, the Gibraltar Skull was sent to [[England]] and exhibited  at the 1864 meeting of the [[British Association for the Advancement of Science]], with its similarity to the Neander Valley remains noted. However, it wasn't until the early [[twentieth century]] that it was realized that Gibraltar 1 was the skull of a Neanderthal. If its significance had been understood in the [[nineteenth century]], Neanderthal Man would probably have been Gibraltar Man.<ref name=seven/><ref name=geology/><ref name=hominid/>  

More evidence of Neanderthal occupation was found at the Devil's Tower [[Mousterian]] rock shelter, also at the north face of the Rock of Gibraltar. In 1926, the skull of a Neanderthal child, [[Gibraltar 2]] or Devil's Tower Child, was discovered by [[archaeologist]] [[Dorothy Garrod]].<ref name=geology/><ref name=hominid>{{cite web|title=Hominid Hunting - The Rock of Gibraltar: Neanderthals' Last Refuge|url=http://blogs.smithsonianmag.com/hominids/2012/09/the-rock-of-gibraltar-neanderthals-last-refuge/|date=19 September 2012|publisher=[[Smithsonian Institution]]|accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|coauthors=Buxton, L. H. Buxton; Smith, E. Elliot; Bate, Dorothea M. A.|title=Excavation of a Mousterian Rock-shelter at Devil's Tower, Gibraltar|journal=The Journal of the Royal Anthropological Institute of Great Britain and Ireland|year=1928|url=http://www.jstor.org/discover/10.2307/4619528?uid=3739656&uid=2129&uid=2&uid=70&uid=4&uid=3739256&sid=21101128994853|accessdate=9 October 2012|author=Garrod, Dorothy A. E.|publisher=[[Royal Anthropological Institute of Great Britain and Ireland]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Gibraltar 2|url=https://www.nespos.org/display/PublicNesposSpace/Devil's+Tower+-+individuum+(Gibraltar+2)|work=nespos.org|publisher=[[Nespos]]|accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref> In the 1940s, Devil's Tower ({{lang-es|La Torre del Diablo}}) was demolished by order of the [[Governor of Gibraltar]], [[Noel Mason-Macfarlane|General Sir Frank Noel Mason-Macfarlane]]. The reason given for the demolition was that the observation tower was in the line of fire of one of Gibraltar's guns.<ref name=discover>{{cite web|title=Sections from the above Map - East side|url=http://www.discovergibraltar.com/pages/gibmap/gibfrm.htm|work=discovergibraltar.com|publisher=DiscoverGibraltar.com|accessdate=8 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The People of Gibraltar - 1704 - Committing a Thousand Excesses|url=http://gibraltar-intro.blogspot.com/2010/10/chapter-2.html|publisher=Neville Chipulina|accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref> 

