==Recent history==

[[File:Nueva terminal gibraltar.JPG|thumb|240px|right|New terminal at [[Gibraltar International Airport]]]]
In May 2007, the Government of Gibraltar revealed plans for the new terminal at Gibraltar International Airport, as well as the new road to the North Front. Following the [[C<U+00F3>rdoba Airport Agreement]], it was decided that the main road that led to the area north of the airport runway would no longer cross the runway. Rather, it would be diverted, such that its first leg was along Devil's Tower Road. At the junction with Eastern Beach Road, there would be a roundabout. The new road, a four lane road, with two lanes in each direction, would U-turn to the north and parallel Eastern Beach Road. Then, it would go through a tunnel at the eastern end of the runway. After emerging on the north, the new road would parallel the frontier extending to the west. The road would then split, with one branch to the terminal, North Front, and Winston Churchill Avenue, and the other to the loop and frontier. Winston Churchill Avenue would continue to cross the runway, but would only be used for emergencies or other exceptions. Pedestrian traffic across the runway would be unchanged.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Air Terminal at Gibraltar Airport|url=http://www.gibraltarairterminal.com/at-the-airport/airport-news/41-airport/122-new-air-terminal-at-gibraltar-airport.html|work=gibraltarairterminal.com|publisher=GibraltarAirTerminal.com|accessdate=9 October 2012|date=17 May 2007}}</ref> 

In May 2009, the government announced that Devil's Tower Road would be changed to a [[divided highway]], to connect the new road at the North Front with Winston Churchill Avenue. In addition, the route of the eastern end of Devil's Tower Road would be adjusted to link it with the new roundabout adjacent to [[Eastern Beach, Gibraltar|Eastern Beach]]. The redevelopment of the road continued into 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Road to North Front - Devil's Tower Road Works|url=http://www.gibraltar.gov.gi/latest_news/press_releases/2009/105-2009.pdf|work=gibraltar.gov.gi|publisher=[[Government of Gibraltar]]|accessdate=8 October 2012|date=21 May 2009}}</ref><ref name=removed>{{cite news|title=Two Bishops' Names See Devil Removed From Our Streets|url=http://www.chronicle.gi/headlines_details.php?id=21735|accessdate=8 October 2012|newspaper=[[Gibraltar Chronicle]]|date=17 May 2011}}</ref> After the change of Devil's Tower Road to a dual carriageway, parking on the road was eliminated. Instead, parking spaces were made available at a new parking garage on Devil's Tower Road and an enlarged parking lot at Forbes' Quarry.<ref>{{cite news|title=Government establishes North District Pilot Parking Scheme|url=http://www.7daysgibraltar.com/article.php?id=4677|accessdate=8 October 2012|newspaper=7 Days - Gibraltar's Free Weekly Newspaper}}</ref>

In May 2011, the Government of Gibraltar revealed that it was renaming Devil's Tower Road as North Front Avenue. The Government indicated that the change was justified by the slight realignment of the eastern portion of the road, such that it would no longer pass in close proximity to the former site of Devil's Tower. However, that proposal met with opposition due to the historical significance of the road, as well as the unnecessary inconvenience to residents. Both the [[Gibraltar Heritage Trust]] and the [[Progressive Democratic Party (Gibraltar)|Progressive Democratic Party]] expressed their opposition.<ref name=vox/><ref name=removed/><ref>{{cite news|title=Heritage Trust Supports Retaining Old Street Names|url=http://www.chronicle.gi/headlines_details.php?id=21879|accessdate=9 October 2012|newspaper=Gibraltar Chronicle|date=2 June 2011}}</ref> The [[Gibraltar Socialist Labour Party]] (GSLP)/Liberal Opposition suggested instead that the road be named Bishop Devlin Avenue to commemorate the late Bishop [[Bernard Patrick Devlin|Bernard Devlin]], the former pastor of St. Theresa's Church.<ref>{{cite news|title=Opposition Suggest Devil's Tower Name to be Wholly Changed|url=http://www.chronicle.gi/headlines_details.php?id=20948|accessdate=8 October 2012|newspaper=Gibraltar Chronicle|date=27 January 2011}}</ref> On 2 June 2011, a one hour silent protest organized by lawyer Patrick Canessa was held over the announced plans to change the names of both Devil's Tower Road and [[Cannon Lane]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Save Cannon Land and Devil's Tower Road - 1 hour silent protest|url=http://www.facebook.com/events/133560173388008/?ref=nf|work=facebook.com|publisher=[[Facebook]]|accessdate=8 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Protestors Fire Broadside over Cannon Lane|url=http://www.chronicle.gi/headlines_details.php?id=21899|accessdate=9 October 2012|newspaper=Gibraltar Chronicle|date=4 June 2011}}</ref>   

The Spanish-based construction firm Obrasc<U+00F3>n Huarte Lain (OHL) had been awarded in 2008 the <U+00A3>34M contract for the airport tunnel project, to design and build a 1.24 km four lane road that would connect Devil's Tower Road with the Gibraltar-Spain border.<ref name=olive/> The Government of Gibraltar cancelled the contract with OHL, effective 12 August 2011, due to "the contractor<U+2019>s failure to comply with the terms of the contract and to proceed with the works as required by the contract."<ref>{{cite news|title=Govt Terminates OHL Contract After 'Lack of Progress'|url=http://www.chronicle.gi/headlines_details.php?id=22343|accessdate=10 October 2012|newspaper=Gibraltar Chronicle|date=1 August 2011}}</ref> The project had been on hold since December 2010.<ref>{{cite news|title=Airport "Tunnel" Contractor Abandons Project|url=http://vox.gi/local/3968-airport-tunnel-contractor-abandons-project.html|accessdate=10 October 2012|newspaper=Vox - The Truly Independent Gibraltar Newspaper|date=10 July 2011}}</ref> In May 2012, it was announced that the firm OHL was suing the Government of Gibraltar for breach of contract.<ref name=olive/><ref>{{cite news|title=Airfield Tunnel Contractor Sues Gib Govt for <U+00A3>20M|url=http://www.chronicle.gi/headlines_details.php?id=24741|accessdate=10 Oct 2012|newspaper=Gibraltar Chronicle|date=4 May 2012}}</ref> It was reported that the local company JBS had taken over the project.<ref name=olive>{{cite news|title=Tunnel contractor sues Gibraltar government for <U+00A3>20 million|url=http://www.theolivepress.es/spain-news/2012/05/14/tunnel-contractor-sues-gibraltar-government-for-20-million/|accessdate=8 October 2012|newspaper=The Olive Press|date=14 May 2012|author=Bryce, James}}</ref> However, in August 2012, the Government of Gibraltar started a new tender process for construction of an access road and tunnel, with the closing date for submission of bids 12 Oct 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=Green light for airport tunnel|url=http://www.gbc.gi/news/231/green-light-for-airport-tunnel|accessdate=10 October 2012|newspaper=GBC News|date=10 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Govt Seeks Tenders for Airport Tunnel and Road|url=http://www.chronicle.gi/headlines_details.php?id=25705|accessdate=10 October 2012|newspaper=Gibraltar Chronicle|date=13 August 2012}}</ref>   

==Notable buildings and monuments on Devil's Tower Road== 

* The [[North Front Cemetery]], established in 1756, is the only cemetery still in use in Gibraltar. A section for [[Jews]] was opened in 1848, after [[Jews' Gate Cemetery]] on [[Windmill Hill]] was closed for burials on 6 May 1848.<ref>{{cite web|title=North Front Cemetery|url=http://www.aboutourrock.com/sites/nfcemetery.htm|work=aboutourrock.com|publisher=About Our Rock|accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Windmill Hill (Jews<U+2019> Gate) Cemetery|url=http://www.jewishgibraltar.com/interest.php|work=jewishgibraltar.com|publisher=Gibraltar Jewish Community|accessdate=10 October 2012|author=Hassid, Rabbi Roni}}</ref> The North Front Cemetery is the only [[Commonwealth War Graves Commission]] Cemetery in Gibraltar.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cemetery Search|url=http://www.cwgc.org/find-a-cemetery.aspx?cpage=1|work=cwgc.org|publisher=[[Commonwealth War Graves Commission]]|accessdate=10 October 2012}}</ref> 

* The [[North Front Cemetery#Gibraltar Memorial|Gibraltar Memorial]] and the [[North Front Cemetery#Gibraltar Cross of Sacrifice|Gibraltar Cross of Sacrifice]] were erected by the Commonwealth War Graves Commission at the corner of Devil's Tower Road and Winston Churchill Avenue. The monuments commemorate the fallen of [[World War I]] and [[World War II].<ref>{{cite web|title=Gibraltar (North Front) Cemetery|url=http://www.cwgc.org/find-a-cemetery/cemetery/54318/GIBRALTAR%20(NORTH%20FRONT)%20CEMETERY|work=cwgc.org|publisher=Commonwealth War Graves Commission|accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref>  

* The foundation stone of the new [[St. Theresa's Church, Gibraltar|St. Theresa's Church]] was laid in 1992 by Bishop Devlin. St. Theresa's had formally become a parish in 1974. However, Mass has been celebrated for "parishioners" since the end of World War II.<ref name=seven/>

* [[Devil's Tower Camp]] is the headquarters of the [[Royal Gibraltar Regiment]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The World's 18 Strangest Military Bases|url=http://www.popularmechanics.com/technology/engineering/architecture/strangest-military-bases-gallery-devils-tower-camp#slide-7|work=popularmechanics.com|publisher=[[Popular Mechanics]]|accessdate=10 October 2012}}</ref> It is one of the four major remaining [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] sites, the others being the Naval Base, the Airfield, and Four Corners.<ref>{{cite news|title=MOD Lands Deal: Govt Unveils Huge New Property Portfolio|url=http://www.chronicle.gi/headlines_details.php?id=22347|accessdate=10 October 2012|newspaper=Gibraltar Chronicle|date=1 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Government announces details of the recent Lands Agreement with MOD|url=http://www.7daysgibraltar.com/article.php?id=5112|accessdate=10 October 2012|newspaper=7 Days - Gibraltar's Free Weekly Newspaper}}</ref> 

* The [[Princess Royal Medical Centre]] at Devil's Tower Camp replaced the [[Royal Naval Hospital Gibraltar]], which closed in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=Healthcare & Hospitals - PIctures: BMH/RNH Gibraltar|url=http://www.archhistory.co.uk/taca/healthhosp.html|work=archhistory.co.uk|publisher=The Army Children Archive (TACA)|accessdate=10 October 2012}}</ref> The following year, on 5 March 2009, the medical centre was inaugurated by [[Anne, Princess Royal]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Princess Royal visits Gibraltar again|journal=Rock Talk|date=July 2009|issue=2|url=http://friendsofgibraltar.org.uk/docs/1279458404Rock%20Talk%202.pdf|accessdate=10 October 2012|page=9}}</ref>  

* The [[Devil's Tower Emplacement]] is a [[World War II]] monument. A plaque on the [[bunker]] reads: "The Devil's Tower Emplacement Guarding The Caledonian Canal and Tank Trap which Existed Some Metres In Front Of This Spot During World War II (1939 -1945)."<ref>{{cite web|title=Devils Tower Emplacement Gibraltar|url=http://en.tracesofwar.com/article/24519/Devils-Tower-Emplacement-Gibraltar.htm|work=en.tracesofwar.com|publisher=STIWOT (Stichting Informatie Wereldoorlog Twee)|accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref>

